# MediQuery — Cursor Rules

## Project
Clinical document intelligence platform. Users upload medical PDFs,
ask natural language questions, get grounded cited answers via
agentic RAG. Never hallucinate — always cite sources.

## Stack
- Next.js 14 App Router + TypeScript (strict)
- Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui
- Gemini API (gemini-1.5-pro + text-embedding-004)
- PostgreSQL + pgvector via Supabase
- Prisma ORM
- NextAuth.js (Google OAuth)
- Upstash Redis (rate limiting)
- Vercel deployment

## Folder structure
src/app/          → pages and API routes
src/lib/ai/       → Gemini client, embeddings, chunker, agent
src/lib/db/       → Prisma client singleton
src/components/   → UI and feature components
src/types/        → TypeScript interfaces

## Coding rules — always follow
- TypeScript only, never use "any"
- "use client" only when useState/useEffect/events needed
- All imports use @/ alias, never relative paths
- Prisma client from @/lib/db/prisma only
- Gemini client from @/lib/ai/gemini only
- Every async function has try/catch error handling
- Commit messages: feat/fix/chore prefix

## AI pipeline
PDF → extract text → chunk (512 chars, 50 overlap) →
embed (text-embedding-004, 768 dims) → store pgvector →
query → embed question → cosine similarity search →
agent checks confidence (threshold 0.75) →
reformulate if low → stream answer → cite sources

## Key decisions
- pgvector over Pinecone: no separate service needed
- 512 char chunks: best precision on medical terminology
- 0.75 similarity threshold: agent reformulates below this
- Streaming always: Gemini takes 3-8s, streaming feels fast